{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[2]", "headings": "['Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample']"}, "page_content": "Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample\nIn this context, we propose a new approach that draws synthetic populations from incomplete microsamples. In the context of this study, an incomplete microsamples is one that has missing information on one or more attributes of the sample. We employ a population synthesis model that utilizes the WGAN as proposed by Kim and Bansal (2023). This study's contribution lies in proposing a novel technique in the WGAN training algorithm that enables the model to effectively learn using incomplete training data. The aim of this study is to propose a methodology that can effectively address the challenges associated with missing data while maintaining a degree of accuracy that is at least equivalent to the methods described in the existing literature.\nThe remainder of the paper is structured in the following manner: Section 2 presents the proposed training methodology for the WGAN model. We first briefly present the original WGAN training method and then describe the proposed changes to it. To evaluate and assess the performance of the proposed training method, we used a microsample from a Swedish national travel survey. Section refsec:CaseStudy provides the experimental setup, metric evaluation, results, and discussions on these aspects. Finally, in Section 5, the article concludes by summarizing the analysis.", "type": "Document"}}